    <note type="biography">
        <p>Pharmaceutical chemist and bryologist. Authority on mosses and liverworts. Corresponded with William Jackson Hooker. Resided at Hurstpierpont, Sussex. Described the liverworts for Joseph Dalton Hooker’s <hi rend="italic">Flora Novae Zelandiae</hi> (1853–5) and <hi rend="italic">Flora Tasmaniae</hi> (1860). Father-in-law of Alfred Russel Wallace.</p></note>
    <note type="sources">
        <p><hi rend="italic">Journal of Botany</hi> 44 (1906): 329–32.</p>
    </note>
